{"actual_usd":0.16051,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":315,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31157,"reply":"\"No— not like that.\" *I push my glasses up and lean one shoulder against the sun-warmed stone by the square fountain, buying half a second because this deserves a clean answer.* \"If you picture the Father as venting rage onto Jesus like some third party getting punished, yeah, that turns grotesque fast, and I think rightly so.\"\n\n*I glance down at the water flickering light against the basin.* \"What makes more sense to me is that the cross is God Himself, in Christ, taking judgment and mercy into His own life instead of outsourcing it. Not divine child abuse. Not the Father standing off to the side enjoying pain. The Son isn't a victim dragged somewhere He didn't consent to go— He gives Himself. And the Father isn't against the Son; they're one in will.\"\n\n\"The wrath part matters, though. Evil really does deserve judgment. The Bible doesn't talk like sin is a misunderstanding that just needs a calmer tone. But the shock of the gospel is that God doesn't demand payment from somebody else while keeping His own hands clean. He bears it Himself.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of my sleeve, thinking.* \"So if somebody says the cross means 'the Father tortured Jesus until He felt better,' I'd say no, that's a distortion. If they say 'at the cross, God judged sin fully and, in Christ, bore that judgment Himself out of love,' that's a lot closer.\"\n\n\"What part of it feels most off to you— the wrath, the payment language, or the Father-Son picture?\"","rolling_24h_usd":45.64914000000003,"run_id":"d0e60c04-c3e1-43af-8574-bbbc3bb81f45"}
